  "market_context": "NQ 5-minute chart with bullish continuation bias. Draw on liquidity is buy-side liquidity above (~16980-16989). Down-close candles previously swept lows and displaced higher with a fair value gap, creating a bullish order block. Sell stops rest at ~16944-16948.",
  "key_observation": "After missing the first bullish order block entry, a secondary order block forms when price sweeps the sell-side liquidity and closes back above down-close candles, offering a better risk-to-reward entry using the mean threshold.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Identify draw on liquidity: the high above (buy-side liquidity) as the target for trend continuation.",
    "Locate the original bullish order block: down-close candles that swept lows and displaced higher with a fair value gap.",
    "Note sell stops resting at the lows below, suggesting price may run lower before going higher.",
    "Observe that the first entry at the initial order block is missed, but the low is never violated.",
    "Identify a secondary setup: down-close candles into order block/fair value gap sweep lows, followed by displacement and close over the down-close candles, forming a new order block.",
    "Calculate risk-to-reward: entry at the order block high with stop on the swing low yields only 1.5R to the equal highs target.",
    "Improve R:R by marking the mean threshold of the order block (which also aligns with a small inversion), tightening the entry to achieve 2.5R.",
    "Take the entry at the mean threshold with stop on the swing low and target the buy-side liquidity / equal highs above."
  ],
  "outcome": "Price moved higher and hit the take profit, delivering a 2.5R winner.",
  "lessons": "Missing the first order block entry does not invalidate the setup; a secondary order block often forms on the retest. Using the mean threshold rather than the order block high improves risk-to-reward, and keeping the stop on the swing low protects against wicks while honoring the true invalidation point.",
